welfare state. Killen also explores cultural attitudes toward electricity, the evolution of psychiatric thought and practice, and the status of women workers in Germany's rapidly industrializing economy. Ultimately, he argues that the backlash against the welfare state that occurred during the late Weimar Republic brought about the final decoupling of modernity and nervous illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aElectrificationxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aElectrificationzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aElectrotherapeuticsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aElectrotherapeuticszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aIndustrializationxPsychological aspectsxGermanyxBerlin. 0aIndustrializationzGermanyzBerlinxPsychological aspects. 0aIndustries. 0aMental fatiguexSocial aspectsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aMental fatiguexSocial aspectszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aNeurastheniaxSocial aspectsxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aNeurastheniaxSocial aspectszGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aPsychiatryxHistoryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aPsychiatryzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aRailroadsxEmployeesxMental healthxGermanyxBerlin. 0aRailroadsxEmployeesxMental healthzGermanyzBerlin. 0aSocial changexPsychological aspectsxGermanyxBerlin. 0aSocial changezGermanyzBerlinxPsychological aspects. 0aSoldiersxMental healthxGermanyxBerlin. 0aSoldiersxMental healthzGermanyzBerlin. 0aTelephone operatorsxMental healthxGermanyxBerlin. 0aTelephone operatorsxMental healthzGermanyzBerlin. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aberlin.  abrain.  aelectricity.  aeurope.  afactory workers.  agerman history.  agerman.  agermany.  agreat war.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory.  aindustrial revolution.  ainsanity.  alabor.  alunacy.  amadness.  amanichean teleology.  amedical commun